{
  "texts": [
    "However, such graph-level representation learning methods adopt a flattened perspective to some extent.",
    "It flattens the graph so that all nodes interact with each other through edges in the same dimension, and such treatment tends to ignore the complex topological information inherent in the graph when selecting representative nodes.",
    "In addition, the traditional graph neural networks commonly pass information with the help of connections between nodes, but they are not designed to directly support the effective aggregation of node features through hierarchical structures.",
    "It is also worth noting that different nodes in the graph often carry different information, and the graph itself may also contain various substructures, in which each node and its substructure play a unique function and affect the construction process of the layer representation.",
    "Therefore, if we want to practically improve the graph-level representation learning capability, the key lies in the ability to fully capture the global contextual information and local node information of the graph."
  ]
}